# Responsive Layout Standards

- The application must remain usable and visually consistent on desktop, tablet (iPad), and phone screens.
- Prefer fluid layouts over fixed pixel widths for main workspaces and modals.
- Reuse existing responsive patterns before inventing new ones.

## Breakpoints (align with current CSS)

| Max width | Typical target |
|-----------|----------------|
| `980px` | Top navigation wraps; nav items stack in pairs |
| `900px` | Two-column accounting/cheque panels become single column |
| `720px` | Dense form grids collapse to one column |

## Layout rules

- Use `flex-wrap: wrap` and `grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(...))` for toolbars, stat cards, and form grids.
- Tables inside `.table-shell` must allow horizontal scroll on narrow screens (`overflow-x: auto`) rather than clipping content.
- Modals use unified size: `width: min(1280px, 98vw)`, `max-height: 96vh`, `overflow: auto` (see popup-size-standards).
- Touch targets: buttons and nav items should remain comfortably tappable on tablets/phones (avoid tiny-only click areas).
- Sticky headers in long modals and workspaces should remain visible when scrolling on mobile.

## When adding a new screen or workspace

- [ ] Test at ~1280px, ~768px, and ~390px viewport width
- [ ] Ensure top nav and workspace content do not overlap
- [ ] Ensure tables scroll horizontally if columns do not fit
- [ ] Avoid horizontal page overflow (`overflow-x` on `body` should stay hidden unless intentional)

## Do not

- Introduce fixed-width layouts that break below 1024px without a media query.
- Hide critical actions on mobile without an alternative access path.
- Create one-off modal sizes per page.
